When a small group of living beings (a small population) separates from the main population from which they originate (for example, if they cross a mountain range or a river, or leave for a new island so that way that they cannot return easily), they are often found in a different environment than they were previously.
This new environment has different resources and different competences, so the new population will need different characteristics or adaptations to be a stronger competitor than it needed to be until that time.
The original population has not changed at all; they still need the same adaptations as before.
Over time, when the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, it also begins to look less and less like the rest of the population.
Finally, after billions or even millions of years, the two populations will have such a different appearance that they cannot be considered the same species.
This process is called speciation, which simply means the formation of new species. Speciation is an inevitable consequence and a fundamental part of evolution.
