Technological determinism is a term that encompasses a wide range of ideas in practice, from technological impulse or technological imperative to a strict sense that human destiny is driven by an underlying logic associated with scientific law and its manifestation in technology.
Much of the interpretations of technological determinism share two main ideas: that the development of technology itself follows a route that goes beyond cultural or political influence and that technology has “effects” in societies that are inherent, rather than socially conditioned.
For example, it could be said that forcibly cars lead to the development of roads.
However, a national road network is not economically viable for a handful of cars, so new production methods are designed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
The ownership of mass vehicles also generates a higher incidence of road accidents, leading to the invention of new techniques in health care to repair injured bodies.
